Description:The goal of this script  is parameter optimization: the script tunes two scalars
(MU,DELTA ) that scale shift Urry hydropathy scale respectively) so that the protein's Radius of Gyration matches the experimental target.
                                                     Workflow
1)Before this script is run the protein chain is simulated for mu=0 and delta=0 for 10 ns to have a stable configuration.The script used can be modified for 
 from the Single Chain MD simulation script uploaded here to restore the bead positions, velocities, and the thermostat state, together with the current force-field 
parameters MU and DELTA in .npz file.
2) Each iteration has two phases.First a non-differentiable production run (2ps NVT steps at 300 K) lets the chain explore conformations under 
the current μ,Δ and gives a fresh, equilibrated starting state. Then a differentiable rollout re-runs for 1ps(10 k steps dt=0.0001ps) at 300K from that state, recording
Rg(Radius of gyration) every 50 steps, and computes a loss = (mean Rg − target)². Gradients of this loss with respect to μ and Δ are obtained by backpropagating through 
 all 10,000 integrator steps, and an optimizer updates the parameters.
3)This loop repeats until the production-MD Rg falls within ±0.01 nm
of the target, at which point the script does a final cool down run with the best parameters, saves the optimized parameters and final state, 
and plots the convergence of loss parameters, and Rg.

The protein model is based on HPS Urry Coar
se Grained model with resolution 1 bead 1 amino acid see the paper : 
[1] Dignon GL, Zheng W, Kim YC, Best RB, Mittal J. "Sequence determinants of protein phase
      behavior from a coarse-grained model." PLoS Comput Biol, 2018.
[2] Regy RM, Thompson J, Kim YC, Mittal J. "Improved coarse-grained model for studying
      sequence dependent phase separation of disordered proteins." Protein Science, 2021.
      (Urry hydrophobicity scale.)

